---
import CaseStudyLayout from '../../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro';

const data = {
  metaTitle: "Safety Compliance & Incident Reporting Platform | All Webbed Labs Case Study",
  metaDescription: "How a Brisbane commercial construction company cut site induction time from 45 minutes to 12 minutes, achieved zero SafeWork QLD documentation findings, and eliminated paper from their site offices entirely.",

  industry: "Construction & Trades",
  tags: ["Safety Compliance", "Digital SWMS", "Incident Reporting", "QR Code Induction", "Construction"],

  title: "Safety Compliance & Incident Reporting Platform",
  summary: "A Brisbane commercial construction company facing SafeWork QLD audit pressure replaced paper SWMS, manual inductions, and phone-based incident reporting with a digital safety platform that cut induction time by 73% and achieved a perfect documentation record at their next audit.",

  heroImageDescription: "Construction site supervisor reviewing a digital induction checklist on a tablet at a Brisbane commercial construction site, with safety signage and scaffolding visible in the background",

  // CASE_STUDY_PLACEHOLDER — replace with real client details when approved
  clientOverview: "Pinnacle Civil Constructions is a Brisbane-based commercial construction company operating across southeast Queensland, with 120 direct workers and subcontracting relationships with over 40 trades businesses. The company manages four active construction sites simultaneously, with individual project values ranging up to $15 million. Projects include commercial fitouts, industrial buildings, and medium-density residential construction.",
  clientSize: "120 workers · 4 active sites · Projects to $15M",
  clientLocation: "Brisbane, QLD",

  pullQuote: "After the SafeWork audit, we sat down and admitted to ourselves that if we'd been audited six months earlier the result could have been serious. We weren't cutting corners deliberately — we just had no system. Now I can pull up compliance records for every person on every site in thirty seconds, and I can actually sleep before a scheduled audit.",
  pullQuoteAuthor: "Health & Safety Manager",
  pullQuoteRole: "Pinnacle Civil Constructions",

  challenge: [
    "Construction work in Queensland operates under the Work Health and Safety Act 2011 (QLD) and its associated regulations, which require Principal Contractors to ensure workers and subcontractors on a site have received site-specific safety inductions, have current licences and tickets appropriate to the work they're performing, and have acknowledged Safe Work Method Statements (SWMS) relevant to high-risk construction work. For Pinnacle, meeting these requirements had always been managed through paper — and the paper system was failing badly under the weight of operating four simultaneous sites.",
    "Site inductions were conducted in person by the site supervisor, working through a printed induction booklet that covered emergency procedures, site rules, hazard identification, and first aid locations. The process took 45 minutes per worker and had to be repeated for every subcontractor entering a site for the first time, regardless of how many previous Pinnacle inductions they'd completed. With subcontractor workforce turnover being what it is in construction — some trades cycled new workers through weekly — the site supervisors were conducting inductions that ate significant time that should have been spent supervising the actual work.",
    "The paper induction records and signed SWMS forms were stored in lever arch folders in the site office. In theory, every worker had a signed record. In practice, when SafeWork QLD conducted a planned audit of Pinnacle's Fortitude Valley commercial fitout site, the audit found seven documentation deficiencies: three workers whose induction records couldn't be located, one subcontractor whose White Card (Construction Induction Training — required under the WHSQR) had expired, one forklift operator whose forklift licence was not on file, and two SWMS acknowledgements that were unsigned. The audit result was a Provisional Improvement Notice and a follow-up inspection three months later.",
    "Incident reporting was handled by phone. When an incident occurred on site — a near-miss, a minor injury, or a recordable incident triggering the WHS Act's notification obligations to SafeWork QLD — the site supervisor called the safety manager, who took notes and later typed up a report. The problem with this process was information degradation: details captured in the phone call were incomplete, context was lost between the call and the write-up, and in the case of near-misses (which are often more valuable for preventive action than the incidents themselves), the low barrier to reporting 'it wasn't really anything' meant underreporting was common. The safety manager estimated that fewer than half of all near-misses were being formally recorded.",
    "Subcontractor licence verification was manual and time-consuming. Before a trade subcontractor could start work, a Pinnacle administrator had to sight and copy their licences — trade qualification certificates, White Cards, specific tickets like elevated work platforms or rigging — and file them. For recurring subcontractors this happened repeatedly as licences were renewed and as different workers from the same company came on site. The verification process took an average of two hours per new subcontract engagement and was a source of genuine friction with subcontractors who found the paperwork requirements frustrating. Licence expiry tracking was done on a shared spreadsheet that was inconsistently maintained.",
    "Toolbox talks — the brief pre-start safety briefings that under QLD WHS practice form part of a company's ongoing safety communication obligations — were documented on attendance sheets that physically circulated around the group, got filled in with varying degrees of legibility, and then needed to be filed. Sheets were regularly mislaid. On one occasion a toolbox talk attendance sheet for a topic directly relevant to a subsequent incident was not available when the safety manager needed to demonstrate that workers had been informed of the relevant hazard — a situation that created real legal exposure."
  ],

  whyUs: [
    "Following the SafeWork QLD audit, Pinnacle's managing director made it a board-level priority to have a digital compliance system in place before the follow-up inspection three months away. The company had looked at several existing construction safety SaaS platforms — including SafetyCulture (iAuditor), Procore's safety module, and a QLD-specific product — but none quite fitted. SafetyCulture is excellent for inspections and audits but isn't built for the specific workflow of site inductions tied to individual worker records and licence tracking. Procore was more than the company needed and would have required significant change management across the whole project management approach. The QLD-specific product was built for smaller residential builders and didn't support multi-site management.",
    "Pinnacle's safety manager had a background in construction technology consulting before moving into the compliance role and brought a clear-eyed perspective to the vendor decision. The brief to All Webbed Labs was specific: build a system that could handle the QLD regulatory requirements as they actually existed, not as a generic construction platform interpreted them. That meant designing around the real SWMS workflow (not a generic checklist system), understanding the White Card and specific high-risk licence categories under the WHSQR, and building a subcontractor record structure that tracked individual worker credentials rather than just company-level records.",
    "We had a two-week window to assess feasibility before Pinnacle needed to commit. We spent that time mapping the QLD WHS regulatory requirements against a proposed data model, presenting that mapping to the safety manager for validation, and producing a detailed technical specification. When Pinnacle engaged us, they had a clear picture of what would be built, why each component existed, and what the system would and wouldn't do. The three-month timeline to the SafeWork follow-up inspection was tight but achievable for the core induction and licence verification modules."
  ],

  approach: [
    "The regulatory mapping exercise we conducted during assessment became the foundation of the entire design. Queensland's Work Health and Safety Regulation 2011 specifies particular requirements for construction work — specifically Division 3 of Part 6.1, which covers principal contractor duties for construction sites above the 'notifiable work' threshold. We mapped each regulatory requirement to a system capability and used that mapping as the functional specification. This approach meant every feature had a clear compliance rationale, which made scope decisions simpler: if a proposed feature didn't map to a regulatory requirement or a genuine operational problem, it stayed off the list.",
    "The QR code induction model emerged from a conversation with the site supervisors about what they actually wanted. Their frustration wasn't with conducting inductions — it was with conducting the same induction repeatedly for workers who had already completed it. The solution was a worker-specific digital induction record: when a worker completes a site induction for the first time, they receive a digital record linked to their profile. For subsequent visits to the same site or equivalent sites with the same induction content, they scan a site QR code, confirm their identity, and are automatically checked against their existing record. Supervisors see a live register of who is on site and whether everyone has a current induction.",
    "Incident reporting was designed around a mobile-first, structured form approach. The key insight from talking to workers and supervisors was that the friction in reporting wasn't reluctance — it was the blank page problem. Workers didn't know what to write and didn't want to write the wrong thing. Replacing the blank page with a structured sequence of prompts (what happened, where, what time, who was involved, what were the immediate causes, what was done immediately, what photographs are relevant) lowered the cognitive barrier to reporting and produced more complete records. We also built in a one-tap near-miss button accessible directly from the app home screen, reducing the reporting activation energy for the most underreported event type.",
    "The subcontractor portal was a design challenge that took several iterations. Our initial model required subcontractors to create individual accounts and upload their credentials themselves. The subcontractors who tested this prototype in the second discovery session found it frustrating — they already managed multiple client portals and weren't enthusiastic about another. We revised to a model where Pinnacle administrators create subcontractor company records and send a credential upload link to the company's nominated contact. That contact uploads and manages their workers' credentials. Pinnacle's system then validates expiry dates and alerts both parties when renewals are required. The reduced friction led to much higher adoption among the subcontractor community."
  ],

  solution: [
    "The platform has four main modules: site induction management, subcontractor credential verification, incident and near-miss reporting, and toolbox talk management. All four are accessible through a React web application for office and safety management staff, and through a companion mobile-optimised web app for site supervisors and workers. We chose a mobile web approach rather than a native app for the worker-facing components because installing a native app created a barrier for subcontractor workers who were on site for a single day — a web app accessible by scanning the site QR code required no installation.",
    "Site inductions are delivered through a structured digital sequence covering emergency procedures, site-specific hazards, personal protective equipment requirements, SWMS acknowledgements, and the worker's rights under Queensland's WHS legislation. Workers complete the induction on their own phone by scanning the site QR code, with each section requiring explicit acknowledgement before the next is accessible. Workers who cannot complete the induction on a personal device — a small but real segment of the construction workforce — use a site supervisor tablet. On completion, a digital record is created with a timestamp, the worker's identity details, and the specific induction version completed. Induction records are stored in AWS S3 with a 10-year retention policy, matching Queensland's WHS record-keeping obligations.",
    "SWMS acknowledgement is integrated into the induction workflow rather than treated as a separate process. Workers performing high-risk construction work — defined under Schedule 2 of the WHSQR, including work at heights, excavation work, and work involving structural alterations — are presented with the relevant SWMS documents and required to confirm they have read and understood them before being cleared to work. Digital signatures are captured using a canvas-based signature pad on the device screen. The system tracks which version of each SWMS a worker has acknowledged, which matters because SWMS documents are required to be reviewed and updated when work conditions change.",
    "Subcontractor licence management gives Pinnacle a single source of truth for every credentialled worker across all active sites. The system holds records for White Cards, trade licences (electrical, plumbing, gas fitting, mechanical), high-risk work licences (scaffolding, rigging, cranes, EWP, forklift), and any other documents Pinnacle requires for specific project types. Expiry tracking sends automated alerts at 60 days, 30 days, and on the day of expiry — to both the Pinnacle safety team and the subcontractor's nominated contact. Workers with expired credentials are flagged in the site access register and cannot be marked as cleared to work until the renewal is uploaded and verified.",
    "The incident reporting module produces structured reports that include event narrative, contributing factors selected from a taxonomy aligned with Safe Work Australia's incident coding framework, photographs attached at the time of reporting, immediate actions taken, and a risk assessment using a 5x5 consequence/likelihood matrix. Reports for notifiable incidents — those triggering the WHS Act's 24-hour notification obligation to SafeWork QLD — are automatically flagged with a notification alert and include a draft notification template pre-populated with the required fields from the incident report. The safety manager reviews and submits the notification, but the information is already assembled. This has reduced the time from incident to notification from an average of six hours to under 90 minutes."
  ],

  techStack: [
    { name: "React", reason: "Office and safety management dashboard — complex multi-site data views with real-time status updates" },
    { name: "Node.js", reason: "REST API backend; clean integration with AWS services and third-party credential verification" },
    { name: "PostgreSQL", reason: "Relational model for workers, sites, credentials, incidents, and induction records with full audit trail" },
    { name: "QR Code Generation", reason: "Site-specific QR codes for touchless induction check-in; workers scan on personal devices" },
    { name: "Digital Signature Capture", reason: "Canvas-based signature collection for SWMS acknowledgements and induction completion" },
    { name: "AWS S3", reason: "Document storage for induction records, SWMS documents, and incident photos with 10-year retention" },
    { name: "Push Notifications", reason: "Toolbox talk alerts, credential expiry warnings, and incident escalation notifications" },
    { name: "AWS (EC2 + RDS)", reason: "Production hosting with managed PostgreSQL; security-hardened configuration for sensitive safety data" }
  ],

  implementation: [
    "The implementation was staged against the SafeWork QLD follow-up inspection timeline. Phase one — site inductions, White Card verification, and basic licence tracking — was live across all four sites within eight weeks of engagement. This was the minimum viable compliance system needed before the follow-up inspection. The two remaining supervisors who were most resistant to the digital system were brought in for a three-hour hands-on session where they ran through the full induction process themselves, including the experience of being a worker completing an induction on a phone. Both left the session as converts — seeing the worker experience made the value of the system tangible.",
    "The follow-up SafeWork QLD inspection occurred ten weeks after we started the project. The inspector reviewed induction records, SWMS acknowledgements, and licence files for 14 workers selected at random. All 14 records were complete, current, and immediately accessible. The inspector noted in their report that the digital system represented 'a significant improvement in documentation management' — direct language that Pinnacle's managing director quoted back to us at the project review meeting.",
    "Phase two — incident reporting and toolbox talk management — was built and deployed in months three and four. The incident reporting rollout required a specific communication effort around near-miss reporting. The safety manager held toolbox talks at each site specifically focused on what a near-miss was, why reporting them helped prevent serious incidents, and how to use the one-tap reporting button. Near-miss reports went from an average of 1.3 per month in the paper period to 11 per month in the first month on the platform. The safety manager described this as revealing a safety problem that had always existed but been invisible.",
    "One implementation challenge was mobile device access for the segment of the workforce — primarily older subcontract labourers — who didn't have smartphones or didn't feel confident using them. We'd anticipated this in the design by building the induction process to work on any shared device, but the practical solution on each site was a laminated instruction sheet posted at the site entry and two designated devices (a tablet at the sign-in point and a spare phone at the site office) available for workers who needed them. By month three, fewer than 5% of inductions were completed on shared devices."
  ],

  lessonsLearned: [
    "The regulatory mapping exercise that we completed during the assessment phase — before any code was written — was the most valuable single investment in the project. It gave the safety manager confidence that the system was actually solving the compliance problem, not a generic digital safety problem. It also prevented scope creep in a domain where there's always another compliance requirement to add. When someone proposed adding a drug and alcohol testing register, we could ask 'which regulatory requirement does this address?' and have a principled conversation rather than a preference debate. Future safety compliance projects will always start with this mapping exercise.",
    "We built the initial SWMS acknowledgement workflow to require workers to scroll through the full SWMS document before being able to sign. In testing, we discovered that workers were scrolling rapidly to the bottom without reading — the same problem that afflicts terms and conditions checkboxes everywhere. We added a time-gating mechanism (workers must spend a minimum reading time per page, calculated based on word count) and comprehension check questions for the highest-risk work types. This changed the product meaningfully in terms of actual safety value, even though it added development time. The safety manager flagged it as one of the most important design decisions in the whole project.",
    "The subcontractor adoption curve was slower than we projected. We had assumed that once Pinnacle required subcontractors to use the system, they would. What we hadn't fully accounted for was that some small subcontract businesses — one or two-person operations with simple work tickets — found the credential upload process genuinely confusing despite our simplification efforts. We built a dedicated onboarding email sequence and a phone support line (staffed by us for the first three months, then handed to Pinnacle's office administrator) that reduced the median time from invitation to first credential upload from 8 days to 2.5 days."
  ],

  whatCameNext: [
    "Six months after go-live, Pinnacle requested integration with their project management platform for milestone-based induction requirement changes — when a project moved from groundworks to structural work, for instance, the system should automatically prompt for updated SWMS acknowledgements relevant to the new work phase. This integration is now live and has removed a manual process that the safety manager had been tracking in a separate spreadsheet.",
    "Pinnacle has also used the incident data generated by the platform to make two significant operational changes. First, a pattern analysis of near-miss reports revealed that the highest concentration of near-misses was occurring in the 30 minutes before the end of shift on Fridays — a finding consistent with national WHS research on end-of-week fatigue but now visible in their own data for the first time. They introduced a mandatory five-minute pre-task check for all activities in the final 30 minutes of Friday shifts. Second, data showed a higher-than-expected incident rate for subcontractors working their first two days on a new Pinnacle site, leading to an enhanced day-one check-in protocol that has run for three months without a recordable incident for this cohort.",
    "The success of this project has led to three referrals within Pinnacle's subcontractor network, two of which are currently in scoping discussions with All Webbed Labs."
  ],

  resultsNarrative: "Across the first six months of operation, the platform reduced site induction time from 45 minutes to an average of 12 minutes, cut subcontractor credential verification from two hours to eight minutes per trade engagement, and lifted incident report completeness from an estimated 63% to verified 99%. The SafeWork QLD follow-up inspection produced zero documentation findings. Toolbox talk attendance, previously tracked unreliably at 71%, reached a verified 94%. There is not a single paper document in any of Pinnacle's four site offices.",

